Howard and Patricia Tillem are no strangers to poverty, but just as they approached the breaking point a few years ago, their family was touched by charity and hope. 

     Mr. Tillem was born without the use of much of the left side of his body. His wife, Patricia, has a learning disability. Although she worked in several factory jobs, her disability made it difficult to hold down a permanent position. In December 1986, Mrs. Tillem gave birth to their daughter, Elizabeth, who also suffers from a learning disability.

nytimes_articles.abstract:
Beginning as an imagined life, "Citizen Kane" ended by damaging three real lives. The reputations of William Randolph Hearst and Marion Davies, the movie's undisguised subjects, and the career of Orson Welles, its maker, never recovered. Such is the theme of "The Battle Over Citizen Kane," which combines social history, movie lore a'd psychological interpretation in an engrossing two hours. 

     Tonight's documentary detects a kinship between Hearst, creator of a new kind of journalism and a new kind of empire, and Welles, creator of a new kind of movie. Hearst was in his 70's and Welles was in his 20's when they clashed. They operated in different worlds and their power was of different sorts, but as remembered here by Hearst biographers and Welles collaborators, both were strong-willed, controversy-courting revolutionaries accustomed to getting their  own way.

pages.abstract: Jacques René Chirac was a French politician who served as President of France from 1995 to 2007. He was previously Prime Minister of France from 1974 to 1976 and 1986 to 1988, as well as Mayor of Paris from 1977 to 1995.

pages.title: Nuclear weapons testing
pages.description: Controlled detonation of nuclear weapons for scientific or political purposes
pages.abstract: Nuclear weapons tests are experiments carried out to determine the performance of nuclear weapons and the effects of their explosion. Over 2,000 nuclear weapons tests have been carried out since 1945. Nuclear testing is a sensitive political issue. Governments have often performed tests to signal strength. Because of their destruction and fallout, testing has seen opposition by civilians as well as governments, with international bans having been agreed on. Thousands of tests have been performed, with most in the second half of the 20th century.

nytimes_articles.abstract:
The civil war in Chechnya, once largely confined to the rebel republic, now threatens to spread through the Caucasus and even beyond. The seizure of hostages in neighboring Dagestan and the hijacking of a ferry in Turkish waters  this month reflected this ominous turn in the conflict, which could easily draw in Georgia and Azerbaijan, and possibly Turkey and Iran. 

     A long history of invasions, settlement and mass migrations, combined with the isolation of mountain valleys, have made the Caucasus one of the world's most ethnically diverse and volatile regions.

nytimes_articles.abstract: The South African national dish, bobotie, is a meat pie of coarsely ground lamb with plenty of curry, bay or lemon leaves and fruits, covered with a custard of milk and eggs, as homey and much loved as meatloaf is in the United States.

wiki_events.headline: An explosives-filled truck rams into the gates of the Central Bank of Sri Lanka in Colombo, killing at least 86 people and injuring 1,400.

pages.title: Central Bank of Sri Lanka
pages.description: Monetary authority and regulator of all licensed banks of Sri Lanka
pages.abstract: The Central Bank of Sri Lanka, known until 1985 as the Central Bank of Ceylon, is the central bank of Sri Lanka. It was established in 1950 under the Monetary Law Act No.58 of 1949 (MLA) and in terms of the Central Bank of Sri Lanka Act No. 16 of 2023, the CBSL is a body corporate with perpetual succession and a common seal. The Central Bank has administrative and financial autonomy. The CBSL has two main boards in operation, namely, the Governing Board (GB) and the Monetary Policy Board (MPB).

pages.title: Colombo
pages.description: Largest city of Sri Lanka by population
pages.abstract: Colombo is the largest city of Sri Lanka by population and de facto the commercial capital of Sri Lanka. The Colombo metropolitan area is estimated to have a population of 5.6 million, and 752,993 within the municipal limits. It is the financial centre of the island and a tourist destination. It is located on the west coast of the island. It is also the administrative capital of the Western Province and the district capital of Colombo District.
